th-century women of the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Deaths_in_childbirth]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|16th-century Holy Roman Empress}}\n{{For|other uses of this term|Isabella of Portugal (disambiguation)}}\n{{Original research|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| consort      = yes\n| name         = Isabella of Portugal\n| image        = La emperatriz Isabel de Portugal, por Tiziano.jpg\n| caption      = [[Titian]], ''[[Portrait of Isabella of Portugal]]'', 1548\n| coronation   =\n| succession   = [[Holy Roman Empress]]<br />[[List of Italian queens|Queen consort of Italy]]\n| reign        = 24 February 1530 \u2013 1 May 1539\n| succession1  = [[Queen of the Romans]]<br />[[Queen consort of Spain]]\n| reign1       = 10 March 1526 \u2013 1 May 1539\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]]|1526}}\n| issue        = {{plainlist|\n* [[Philip II, King of Spain]]\n* [[Maria of Spain|Maria, Holy Roman Empress]]\n* [[Joanna of Austria, Princess of Portugal|Joanna, Princess of Portugal]]\n}}\n| house        = [[House of Aviz|Aviz]]\n| father       = [[Manuel I, King of Portugal]]\n| mother       = [[Maria of Aragon, Queen of Portugal|Maria of Aragon]]\n| birth_date   = 24 October 1503\n| birth_place  = [[Lisbon]], Portugal\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1539|5|1|1503|10|24|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]], Spain\n| burial_place = [[El Escorial]]\n| religion     = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n| signature    = Isabel de Avis.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Isabella of Portugal''' (24 October 1503 \u2013 1 May 1539), also known as the \"Empress of the Carnation\", was Holy Roman Empress and Queen of Spain, Germany, and Italy, and Duchess of Burgundy by her marriage to [[Emperor Charles V]]. She was [[Queen regent|regent]] of Spain during her husband's long travels in Europe during 1529-1533, 1535-1536 and 1538-1539. \n\nBorn to [[Manuel I of Portugal]] and [[Maria of Aragon]], Isabella was the granddaughter of the [[Catholic Monarchs]], [[Isabella I of Castile]] and [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]]. Throughout her life, many compared her to her grandmother for her intelligence, character and determination in politics. Her personal motto was \"aut Caesar aut nihil\" ('either Cesar or nothing'). It was thanks to her governorships that Spain was able to remain independent of imperial policies.<ref>S. Jansen: The Monstrous Regiment of Women: Female Rulers in Early Modern Europe, 2002</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n===Childhood===\nIsabella was born in [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]] on October 24, 1503 and named after her maternal grandmother and [[Isabella of Asturias|aunt]], who had been her father's first wife. She was the second child and eldest daughter of King [[Manuel I of Portugal]] and his second wife, [[Maria of Aragon (1482-1517)|Maria of Aragon]]. Isabella was second-in-line to the throne until the birth of her brother [[Luis, Duke of Beja|Luis]] in 1506.\n\nIsabella was educated under the supervision of her mother and her governess, [[Elvira de Mendoza]]. She would progressively become an intelligent young woman, learning [[politics]], [[mathematics]], the languages of [[Latin]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[French language|French]], [[Renaissance]] classics, and the Christian doctrine. In addition to all this, she was possessed a vast library composed of works for prayer and more mundane works which were of her taste, especially on [[cavalry]].\n\n===Engagement===\nAs the oldest daughter of Manuel I of Portugal, Isabella was a rather attractive candidate for marriage. Her mother left in her will, and in a clear message to her husband, the desire that the 14 years-old Isabella should marry only a king or the legitimate son of kings. The ideal candidate for Isabella's husband was her first cousin [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles]], son of Maria's sister, [[Joanna of Castile]], and [[Philip I of Castile]]. A marriage would bring a strong alliance between the kingdoms of Spain and Portugal, in accordance with the wishes of their grandparents, Isabella and Ferdinand: It would facilitate to continue the exploration of the oceans without incurring clashes, as Portugal was the only naval power that could question Spain's supremacy in the Atlantic. As Charles was sovereign of multiple kingdoms, Spain needed allies and it was necessary that Portugal (Christendom's richest kingdom) fall under its orbit and not of France, which had happened in the [[War of Castilian Succession]]. Moreover, the nobles desired Charles's marriage to a princess of Castilian blood from the Iberian peninsula, just like Isabella.\n\nHowever, the 18-year-old King was in no hurry to marry and ignored the nobles' advice, instead sending his sister [[Eleanor of Austria|Eleanor]] to marry Isabella's widowed father in 1518. Charles's Flemish advisors, especially [[William de Cro\u00ff]], later convinced him to relegate the Portuguese alliance to the background and replace it with an alliance with England. In 1521, Charles became engaged to his other first cousin [[Mary I of England|Mary Tudor]], daughter of [[Henry VIII of England]] and [[Catherine of Aragon]], who was sixteen years younger than Charles and still a child. Their engagement sought to undo an alliance between England and France, articulated by the ambitious Cardinal [[Thomas Wolsey]]. Many in Portugal took Isabella's rejection as an offence, but Isabella remained determined and hopeful that she would marry her powerful cousin: The choice was that she would marry only Charles or she would enter a convent.\n\nBy 1525, Charles was no longer interested in an alliance with England and could wait no longer for Mary Tudor to get older, as he was determined to have legitimate children. His engagement was called off, the alliance with England was abandoned, and Charles finally sought to marry Isabella. There were many more advantages - she was closer to him in age (she was only three years his junior), fluent in Spanish, and offered a handsome dowry of 900,000 Portuguese cruzados or Castilian folds, which was more than enough to solve many of his economic and financial problems brought on by the [[Italian War of 1521-26]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Tracy|first=James D.|title=Emperor Charles V, Impresario of War : campaign strategy, international finance, and domestic politics|year=2002|publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press|isbn=9780521814317|page=114|edition=}}</ref> The negotiations and marriage contract for an alliance with Portugal were made - Isabella would marry Charles and her brother, King [[John III of Portugal]], would marry Charles's youngest sister, [[Catherine of Austria, Queen of Portugal|Catherine of Austria]].\n\n==Holy Roman Empress and Queen of Spain==\n[[File:Charles V and Empress Isabella of Portugal, by Peter Paul Rubens.jpg|thumb|right|Emperor Charles V and Empress Isabella. [[Peter Paul Rubens]] after [[Titian]], 17th century]]\n{{refimprove|section|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Marriage and Honeymoon===\nIn January 1526, Isabella travelled to Spain. Upon her arrival, she met a by the [[Duke of Calabria]], the [[Archbishop of Toledo]] and the [[Duke of B\u00e9jar]] at the Spanish-Portuguese border. They escorted her to [[Seville]], where she was to wait for Charkes for a week. Their wedding took place that very same day just after midnight on 11 March in the Palace of [[Alc\u00e1zar of Seville]].<ref>{{cite book|last=MacQuarrie|first=Kim|title=The Last Days of the Incas|url=https://archive.org/details/lastdaysofincas00macq|url-access=registration|year=2007|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=1416539352|page=[https://archive.org/details/lastdaysofincas00macq/page/35 35]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ford|first=Richard|title=A Hand-Book for Travellers in Spain, and Readers at Home: Describing the Country and Cities, the Natives and Their Manners|year=2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=1108037534|page=258}}</ref> \n\nAlthough their marriage was originally a political arrangement, Isabella captivated her husband with her charm and beauty. Following their wedding, the couple spent a long honeymoon at the [[Alhambra]] in [[Granada]] and records show that during their honeymoon \"when [Charles and Isabella] are together, although there are many people around, they do not notice anyone else; they talk and laugh, and nothing else distracts them.\"{{quote needs citation|date=August 2018}} Charkes ordered the seeds of a Persian flower, that had never been seen before in Spain, to be planted in the gardens of the Alhambra. The seeds eventually grew into the red carnation and Isabella was so delighted by the new flower that her husband ordered thousands more to be planted in her honour. The red carnation later became Spain's [[floral emblem]].\n\n===Regency===\n[[File:Isabel de Portugal, Pompeo Leoni.jpg|thumb|left|The bronze statue of Empress Isabella by [[Leone Leoni]], 1550-1555, that was commissioned by Charles V, on display at the [[El Prado Museum]], [[Madrid]].]]\n\nIsabella proved to be a very competent politician when she served as [[List of Spanish regents|regent of Spain]] during her husband's absences due to political affairs and [[wars]] abroad between 1529\u20131532 and 1535\u20131539. She attended meetings of the governing councils, consulted with the ministers, and eventually\ntook a more active role in the policy-making process. The Emperor was impressed with many of her accomplishments and decisions.\n\nAll the documentation of the time indicates{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} that Isabella was a profound connoisseur of the problems of the peninsular kingdoms, defending intransigently the good common to particular interests. At the external level, her sensible actions were decisive in the defence of the coasts of the peninsula and of [[North Africa]], those [[investment|invested]] by [[piracy]].\n\nDuring her time as regent, Isabella traveled a lot around Spain, defending the royal power and the monarch's supreme authority. She traveled regularly in the autumn between [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]], [[Valladolid]], Seville, [[Barcelona]] and [[Majorca]]. To deal with important matters of the empire, Charles and Isabella wrote to each other regularly. Sometimes, the Emperor didn't write for months, to the point that the Empress \"scolded\" him in one letter, saying that at least, she would write \"every twenty days.\"{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===Life at Court===\nWhen she heard that her husband was about to return, Isabella sent receptions with large parties. However, the time she was alone with her children, [[ladies-in-waiting]], and counselors of the court, she had a simpler life.\n\nIsabella ensured that their children's educations, especially that of her son [[Philip II of Spain|Philip]], were very completed. She even personally taught them her native language, [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]].\n\n==Health and Death==\n{{cns|date=August 2018|text=Isabella suffered from [[tertian fever]]s, which became chronic later in her life. She also suffered several times from malaria, causing her health to be very fragile. Due to the very hot weather of Toledo and Seville, she spent the summers in the milder [[Avila, Spain|Avila]] because she suffered several times from illness. She had a total of seven pregnancies, out of which five were successful, and suffered two miscarriages. Her husband's absences caused her great loneliness, which some historians believe further weakened her delicate health.|reason=}} There is also speculation that Isabella may have suffered from consumption and its effects debilited her further. A contemporary described her not long before her death: \"The Empress is the greatest pity in the world; she is so thin as to not resemble a person.\"\n\nIn 1539, Isabella became pregnant for the seventh time, but in the third month of the pregnancy she contracted another fever that caused antenatal complications and gave birth to a stillborn son. She died two weeks later on 1 May 1539 at the age of 35.<ref>Geoffrey Parker (2014), ''Imprudent King: A New Life of Philip II'', New Haven and London: Yale University Press, p. 12. {{ISBN|9780300196535}}</ref> The Emperor was left so devastated by his wife's death that he couldn't bring himself to accompany her body to the [[Royal Chapel of Granada]], the burial place of the [[Catholic Monarchs]]. Instead, he instructed their son Philip to accompany his mother's body with [[Francis Borgia, 4th Duke of Gand\u00eda]]. When Borgia conveyed Isabella's remains and saw the effects of [[decomposition]] on the beautiful empress, he decided to \"never again serve a mortal master\".{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} After his own wife's death in 1541, Borgia retired from court and became a Jesuit priest.\n\nIn the aftermath, Charles locked himself up in a monastery for two months, where he prayed and mourned for his wife alone, but never recovered from Isabella's death; he never remarried and dressed in black for the rest of his life. He died on 21 September 1558, holding in his hand the cross that his wife had been holding when she died.\n\n===Post-mortem Tributes and Reburials===\n[[File:La Gloria (Tiziano).jpg|thumb|right|Titian's ''La Gloria'', one of the several paintings commissioned by Charles V in memory of his wife Isabella]]\nIn memory of Isabella, Charles commissioned several tributes through art and music, beginning in 1540 when he commissioned the Flemish composer [[Thomas Crecquillon]] to compose new music in honour of the Empress. Crecquillon composed his ''Missa Mort m'a priv\u00e9'' as a memorial to Isabella, which expresses the Emperor's grief and great wish for a heavenly reunion with his beloved wife.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.brabantensemble.com/discography/thomas-crecquillon-missa-mort-ma-prive-motets-and-chansons/|title= Thomas Crecquillon: Missa 'Mort m\u2019a priv\u00e9', motets and chansons|last=Ham |first=Martin |date=2006 |website= The Brabant Ensemble| access-date=23 October 2018}}\n</ref> Another musical tribute to Isabella is ''Carole cur defles Isabellam'' that was composed in 1545 by the Franco-Flemish composer [[Nicolas Payen]].\n\nIn 1543, Charles commissioned his favourite painter [[Titian]] to paint posthumous portraits of Isabella by using earlier ones of her as his model. Titian painted several portraits of the Empress, which included his ''[[Portrait of Isabella of Portugal|Portrait of The Empress Isabel of Portugal]]'' and ''[[La Gloria (Titian)|La Gloria]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.museodelprado.es/en/the-collection/art-work/the-glory/66149817-6f88-4e5f-a09a-81f63a84d145|title= The Glory.  1551 \u2013 1554. Oil on canvas|website= Museo del Prado (Prado Museum)| access-date=23 October 2018}}</ref> He also painted a double portrait of Charles and Isabella together, of which there is a copy by [[Peter Paul Rubens]]. Charles kept these portraits with him whenever he travelled and after he retired to the [[Monastery of Yuste]] in 1555.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.museodelprado.es/en/the-collection/art-work/the-empress-isabel-of-portugal/d4eddf35-c76c-4c11-8f2b-099f7b71d696|title= The Empress Isabel of Portugal|website= Museo del Prado (Prado Museum)| access-date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cenotafio de Carlos I de Espa\u00f1a y su familia.jpg|thumb|left|The bronze effigies of Charles and Isabella at the Basilica in El Escorial]]\nIn 1574, the body of Empress Isabella was transferred by her son Philip II to the [[El Escorial|Royal Monastery of San Lorenzo de El Escorial]], where she was originally interred into a small vault along with her husband directly underneath the altar of the Royal Chapel. This was done in accordance with Charles's last will and testament, in which he left a [[codicil (will)|codicil]] asking for the establishment of a new religious foundation in which he and Isabella would be reburied together side by side, \"half-body under the altar and half under the priest's feet\". They remained in the Royal Chapel while the famous Basilica of the Monastery and the Royal Crypt were still under construction.\n\nIn 1654, after the Basilica and Royal Crypt were finally completed during the reign of their great-grandson [[Philip IV of Spain|Philip IV]], the remains of Charles and Isabella were moved into the Royal Pantheon of Kings, which lies directly under the Basilica.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delacuadra.net/escorial/textos/1997c-a-panteo.pdf |title=A-Panteo.Pdf |date= |accessdate=2019-06-10}}</ref> On one side of the Basilica are bronze effigies of Charles and Isabella, with effigies of their daughter [[Maria of Austria, Holy Roman Empress|Maria of Austria]] and Charles's sisters, [[Eleanor of Austria]] and [[Mary of Hungary (governor of the Netherlands)|Maria of Hungary]], behind them. Exactly adjacent to them on the opposite side of the Basilica are effigies of their son Philip with three of his wives and their ill-fated grandson, [[Carlos, Prince of Asturias]].\n\n==Issue==\n{| style=\"text-align:center; width:100%\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Name !! style=\"width:100px;\"| Portrait !! Lifespan !! Notes \n|-\n| '''[[Philip II of Spain]]'''<br />\n|| [[File:Portrait of Philip II of Spain by Sofonisba Anguissola - 002b.jpg|120px]]\n|| 21 May 1527 \u2013<br/> 13 September 1598\n|| Only surviving son, successor of his father in the Spanish crown. As a grandson of [[Manuel I of Portugal]] through Isabella, he was in the line of succession to the throne of Portugal and claimed it after his uncle's death ([[Henry I of Portugal|Henry, the Cardinal-King]], in 1580), thus establishing the [[Iberian Union]].\n|-\n| '''[[Maria of Austria, Holy Roman Empress|Maria]]'''<br />\n|| [[File:Maria of Spain 1557.jpg|120px]]\n|| 21 June 1528 \u2013<br/>26 February 1603\n|| Married her first cousin [[Maximilian II, Holy Roman Emperor]].\n|-\n| '''Ferdinand'''<br />\n|| [[File:Greater Coat of Arms of Charles I of Spain, Charles V as Holy Roman Emperor (1530-1556).svg|120px]]\n|| 22 November 1529 \u2013<br/> 13 July 1530\n|| Died in infancy.\n|-\n| '''Son'''<br />\n|| [[File:Greater Coat of Arms of Charles I of Spain, Charles V as Holy Roman Emperor (1530-1556).svg|120px]]\n|| 29 June 1534\n||  Stillborn.\n|-\n| '''[[Joanna of Austria, Princess of Portugal|Joanna]]'''<br />\n|| [[File:Alonso S\u00e1nchez Coello - Portrait of Juana of Austria, Princess of Portugal - Google Art Project.jpg|120px]]\n|| 26 June 1535 \u2013<br/>7 September 1573\n|| Married her first cousin [[Jo\u00e3o Manuel, Prince of Portugal]].\n|-\n| '''Juan'''<br />\n|| [[File:Greater Coat of Arms of Charles I of Spain, Charles V as Holy Roman Emperor (1530-1556).svg|120px]]\n|| 19 October 1537 \u2013<br/> 20 March 1538\n|| Died in infancy.\n|-\n| '''Son'''<br />\n|| [[File:Greater Coat of Arms of Charles I of Spain, Charles V as Holy Roman Emperor (1530-1556).svg|120px]]\n|| 21 April 1539\n|| Miscarried and stillborn.\n|}\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Coat of Arms of Isabella of Portugal, Holy Roman Empress and Queen Consort of Spain.svg|Coat of arms of Isabella of Portugal as Empress\n</gallery>\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Isabella of Portugal'''\n|2= 2. [[Manuel I of Portugal]]\n|3= 3. [[Maria of Aragon, Queen of Portugal|Maria of Aragon]]\n|4= 4. [[Ferdinand, Duke of Viseu]]<ref name=\"1911-Emanuel I\">{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Emanuel I. |volume=9}}</ref>\n|5= 5. [[Beatriz, Duchess of Viseu|Beatrice of Portugal]]<ref name=\"1911-Emanuel I\"/>\n|6= 6. [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]]<ref name=\"Liss\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_krkCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT11 |title=Isabel the Queen: Life and Times |last=Liss |first=Peggy K. |date=2015-11-10 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=9780812293203 |pages=11 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|7= 7. [[Isabella I of Castile]]<ref name=\"Liss\"/>\n|8= 8. [[Edward, King of Portugal|Edward I of Portugal]]<ref name=\"Stephens1903\">{{cite book|last=Stephens|first=Henry Morse|title=The Story of Portugal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jwMqAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA139|accessdate=17 September 2018|year=1903|publisher=G.P. Putnam's Sons|page=139}}</ref>\n|9= 9. [[Eleanor of Aragon, Queen of Portugal|Eleanor of Aragon]]<ref name=\"Stephens1903\"/>\n|10= 10. [[John, Constable of Portugal]]<ref name=\"Liss\"/> (= 30)\n|11= 11. [[Isabel of Barcelos]]<ref name=\"Liss\"/> (= 31)\n|12= 12. [[John II of Aragon and Navarre|John II of Aragon]]<ref name=\"1911-Ferdinand\">{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Ferdinand V. of Castile and Leon and II. of Aragon |volume=10}}</ref>\n|13= 13. [[Juana Enr\u00edquez]]<ref name=\"1911-Ferdinand\"/>\n|14= 14. [[John II of Castile]]<ref name=\"Britannica295037\">{{Britannica|295037|Isabella I, Queen of Spain}}</ref>\n|15= 15. [[Isabella of Portugal, Queen of Castile|Isabella of Portugal]]<ref name=\"Britannica295037\"/>\n|16= 16. [[John I of Portugal]]<ref name=\"Stephens1903\"/> (= 20)\n|17= 17. [[Philippa of Lancaster]]<ref name=\"Stephens1903\"/> (= 21)\n|18= 18. [[Ferdinand I of Aragon]]<ref name=\"DeSousa2-497\">{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/historiagenealog02sous#page/496/mode/2up |title=Historia genealogica da casa real portugueza |trans-title=Genealogical History of the Royal House of Portugal |volume=2 |language=pt |last=de Sousa |first=Antonio Caetano |publisher=Lisboa Occidental |year=1735 |page=497}}</ref> (= 24)\n|19= 19. [[Eleanor of Alburquerque]]<ref name=\"DeSousa2-497\"/> (= 25)\n|20= 20. [[John I of Portugal]]<ref name=\"Stephens1903\"/> (= 16)\n|21= 21. [[Philippa of Lancaster]]<ref name=\"Stephens1903\"/> (= 17)\n|22= 22. [[Afonso I, Duke of Braganza]]<ref name=\"Liss\"/>\n|23= 23. [[Beatriz Pereira de A