{"title_page": "Serdika Metro Station", "text_new": "{{Short description|S\u043efia metro station}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name                = [[File:Sofia Metro Logo.svg|27px|link=Sofia Metro]] Serdika\n| style               = Sofia Metro\n| image               = Serdika stantion.jpg\n| coordinates         = {{coord|42|41|52|N|23|19|17|E|display=inline,title}}\n| owned               = [[Sofia#Administration|Sofia Municipality]]\n| platform            = island\n| levels              = 2\n| tracks              = 2\n| connections         = Transfer to [[Serdika II Metro Station|Serdika II]]\n| structure           = sub-surface\n| parking             = Yes\n| code                = 3013; 3014\n| opened              = {{Start date|2000|10|31|df=y}}\n| services            = {{s-rail|title=Sofia Metro}}\n{{s-line|system=Sofia Metro|line=Line 1|previous=Opalchenska|next=SU St. Kliment Ohridski}}\n{{s-line|system=Sofia Metro|line=Line 2|previous=Opalchenska|next=SU St. Kliment Ohridski}}\n| map_locator         = [[File:Map8 eng trans.png|300px]]\n}}\n{{Sofia Metro Red line}}\n{{Sofia Metro Blue line}}\n'''Serdika Metro Station''' ({{lang-bg|\u041c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u044f \u201e\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043a\u0430\u201c}}) is a station on the [[Sofia Metro]] in [[Bulgaria]].  It was put into operation on October 31, 2000.  With the opening of [[Serdika II Metro Station|Serdika II]] on August 31, 2012 the station became a transfer station between the Red and Blue lines. However it is not a true transfer station (such as platforms 3, 4, 5 and 6 of the [[Canning Town station|Canning Town]] station in London), but an interconnected station, in a similar manner to the [[Washington Metro]]'s two [[Farragut North (WMATA station)|Farr]][[Farragut West (WMATA station)|agut]] stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=142808 |title=Bulgaria: Sofia Expands Its Metro, Barroso Pleased - Novinite.com - Sofia News Agency |publisher=Novinite.com |date=2012-08-31 |accessdate=2012-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focus-fen.net/index.php?id=n286275 |title=Jose Manuel Barroso: Sofia subway\u2019s new line is an example of what can be expected from Europe - FOCUS Information Agency |publisher=Focus-fen.net |date= |accessdate=2012-09-30}}</ref>\n\nThe station is named after the ancient city of [[Serdica]], as it lies in the very centre of the hitherto unearthed ruins of that city.<ref>[http://ulpiaserdica.com/images/Serdica_o.png], ''UlpiaSerdica.com'', Retrieved Dec 2012.</ref> These are located about six meters (20 feet) below ground and, along with the opening of Serdika II station, a large section of the old city has been exposed and is in full view both around and inside the two stations. <ref>[http://standartnews.com/balgariya/sofiyantsi_tragvat_po_ulitsite_na_drevna_serdika_-160158.html Sofianites are setting off along the streets of Ulpia Serdica], ''Stendart News (in Bulgarian)'', 8 Aug 2012. Retrieved Dec 2012.</ref>\n\nSerdika is one of only three metro stations in the world where the same line passes through the station twice in a [[pretzel]] configuration, the others being the [[Monument Metro station]] on the [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England, and [[Voorweg RandstadRail station]] on the [[Randstadrail]] in [[The Hague]], Netherlands.\n\n==Public transportation links==\n* [[Sofia Tramway|Tramway service]]: 4, 12, 18\n\n==Location==\n{{Empty section|date=October 2012}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nSerdika.jpg\nSerdika stantion.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline|Serdika (Sofia Metro)|Serdika Metro Station}}\n* [http://metropolitan.bg/panoramas/4.htm 360 degrees panorama from inside the station]\n* [http://www.metropolitan.bg/ Sofia Metropolitan]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20011029075901/http://metropolitan.hit.bg/ Unofficial site]\n\n{{Europe-metro-stub}}\n{{Bulgaria-transport-stub}}\n[[Category:Sofia Metro stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2000]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in Bulgaria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station\n| name                = [[File:Sofia Metro Logo.svg|27px|link=Sofia Metro]] Serdika\n| style               = Sofia Metro\n| image               = Serdika stantion.jpg\n| coordinates         = {{coord|42|41|52|N|23|19|17|E|display=inline,title}}\n| owned               = [[Sofia#Administration|Sofia Municipality]]\n| platform            = island\n| levels              = 2\n| tracks              = 2\n| connections         = Transfer to [[Serdika II Metro Station|Serdika II]]\n| structure           = sub-surface\n| parking             = Yes\n| code                = 3013; 3014\n| opened              = {{Start date|2000|10|31|df=y}}\n| services            = {{s-rail|title=Sofia Metro}}\n{{s-line|system=Sofia Metro|line=Line 1|previous=Opalchenska|next=SU St. Kliment Ohridski}}\n{{s-line|system=Sofia Metro|line=Line 2|previous=Opalchenska|next=SU St. Kliment Ohridski}}\n| map_locator         = [[File:Map8 eng trans.png|300px]]\n}}\n{{Sofia Metro Red line}}\n{{Sofia Metro Blue line}}\n'''Serdika Metro Station''' ({{lang-bg|\u041c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u044f \u201e\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043a\u0430\u201c}}) is a station on the [[Sofia Metro]] in [[Bulgaria]].  It was put into operation on October 31, 2000.  With the opening of [[Serdika II Metro Station|Serdika II]] on August 31, 2012 the station became a transfer station between the Red and Blue lines. However it is not a true transfer station (such as platforms 3, 4, 5 and 6 of the [[Canning Town station|Canning Town]] station in London), but an interconnected station, in a similar manner to the [[Washington Metro]]'s two [[Farragut North (WMATA station)|Farr]][[Farragut West (WMATA station)|agut]] stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=142808 |title=Bulgaria: Sofia Expands Its Metro, Barroso Pleased - Novinite.com - Sofia News Agency |publisher=Novinite.com |date=2012-08-31 |accessdate=2012-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focus-fen.net/index.php?id=n286275 |title=Jose Manuel Barroso: Sofia subway\u2019s new line is an example of what can be expected from Europe - FOCUS Information Agency |publisher=Focus-fen.net |date= |accessdate=2012-09-30}}</ref>\n\nThe station is named after the ancient city of [[Serdica]], as it lies in the very centre of the hitherto unearthed ruins of that city.<ref>[http://ulpiaserdica.com/images/Serdica_o.png], ''UlpiaSerdica.com'', Retrieved Dec 2012.</ref> These are located about six meters (20 feet) below ground and, along with the opening of Serdika II station, a large section of the old city has been exposed and is in full view both around and inside the two stations. <ref>[http://standartnews.com/balgariya/sofiyantsi_tragvat_po_ulitsite_na_drevna_serdika_-160158.html Sofianites are setting off along the streets of Ulpia Serdica], ''Stendart News (in Bulgarian)'', 8 Aug 2012. Retrieved Dec 2012.</ref>\n\nSerdika is one of only three metro stations in the world where the same line passes through the station twice in a [[pretzel]] configuration, the others being the [[Monument Metro station]] on the [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England, and [[Voorweg RandstadRail station]] on the [[Randstadrail]] in [[The Hague]], Netherlands.\n\n==Public transportation links==\n* [[Sofia Tramway|Tramway service]]: 4, 12, 18\n\n==Location==\n{{Empty section|date=October 2012}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nSerdika.jpg\nSerdika stantion.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline|Serdika (Sofia Metro)|Serdika Metro Station}}\n* [http://metropolitan.bg/panoramas/4.htm 360 degrees panorama from inside the station]\n* [http://www.metropolitan.bg/ Sofia Metropolitan]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20011029075901/http://metropolitan.hit.bg/ Unofficial site]\n