e cruiser|Mikuma||2}} and {{ship|Japanese cruiser|Mogami|1934|2}} (both {{navy|Empire of Japan}}).<ref name=\"Imperial cruisers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Mogami_t.htm |title=Imperial cruisers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=6 April 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Dorsetshire|40|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Easter Sunday Raid]]: The {{sclass2-|County|cruiser}} was bombed and sunk in the Indian Ocean {{convert|200|nmi|km}} south west of Ceylon by Japanese aircraft with the loss of 234 of her 653 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Empire Beacon||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The coaster struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Bristol Channel]] off St. Anns Head, [[Pembrokeshire]]\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Feddy||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The cargo ship was lost in a collision with the trawler ''Visenda'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) off [[North Ronaldsay]].<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1127452|shipname=Feddy |accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Gallant|H59|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[G and H-class destroyer|G-class]] [[destroyer]] was bombed and damaged beyond economical repair while being repaired after having previously lost her bow to a mine and being beached at [[Malta]] on 10 January 1941. The wreck was refloated and sunk as a blockship in September, 1943.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/4391.html |title=HMS Gallant (H59) of the Royal Navy |publisher=U Boat.net |accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Harpasa||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk in the [[Bay of Bengal]]  by \"Kate\"s  from {{ship|Japanese aircraft carrier|Ry\u016bj\u014d||2}}. 6 crewmen killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Ryujo_t.htm |title=Imperial Flattops |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=6 April 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Hector|F45|6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Easter Sunday Raid]]: The [[armed merchantman|armed merchant cruiser]] was bombed and sunk at [[Colombo]], Ceylon by Japanese aircraft.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Ninetto G.||2}} \n|flag={{Flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk by {{HMS|Una|N87|6}} ({{navy|United Kingdom}}), east of [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], Italy ({{coord|37|05|N|15|41|E}}). There were 2 dead and 28 survivors.<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5603468|shipname=Ninetto G. |accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=Perdite>{{cite web |url=http://conlapelleappesaaunchiodo.blogspot.com/2014/02/cronologia-delle-perdite_14.html |title=Italian losses |publisher=conlapelleappesaaunchiodo.blogspot.com |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Russian trawler|RT-61||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[naval trawler]] was bombed and sunk at [[Murmansk]] by [[Luftwaffe]] aircraft.<ref name=seekrieg194204/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Soli||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was bombed and damaged at [[Columbo]], [[Ceylon]] by [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] aircraft. She was declared a total loss and beached. She was refloated on 4 January 1952 and subsequently scrapped at [[Karachi]], Pakistan.<ref name=Soli>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/soli.html |title=D/T Soli |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Tenedos|H04|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass2-|S|destroyer|||1917}} was bombed and sunk at Colombo by Japanese aircraft with the loss of 33 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Washingtonian|1919|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|des